Toby Ellis, Esq. 2025-07-25 02:53 p.m.
Your Honour,

I respectfully move this Honourable Court to dismiss the present action in its entirety, with prejudice, on the grounds that the prosecution has failed to establish sufficient probable cause to justify this indictment. The State’s case rests exclusively upon a Search Warrant which, I submit, is procedurally defective and legally void ab initio.

The warrant in question was issued outside of the proper procedural framework established by this Court's binding Local Rules and in direct contravention of repeated judicial directives concerning warrant applications. Specifically, District Mayflower Local Rule 4(7)(1) provides unequivocally that:
“All pre-court submissions must be filed through the court’s electronic Discord system, known as judicialFLOW.”

This rule is mandatory in nature. It admits of no exception and applies uniformly to all judicial officers. The Search Warrant used against my client was not submitted via judicialFLOW, but instead was procured through informal, off-record communications—an act in clear breach of the rule. No provision exists within the Local Rules permitting a judge to circumvent the judicialFLOW system by personal discretion, and accordingly, all such warrants issued contrary to this rule must be deemed procedurally improper.

Furthermore, District Mayflower Local Rule 4(7)(2) states as follows:
“No case will be admitted to the court without completing this process.”

This rule reinforces the procedural necessity of compliance with judicialFLOW for initiating valid judicial proceedings. The Search Warrant being the sole basis for the charges levied against my client, and the same being obtained in violation of mandatory procedural rules, renders the entire foundation of this indictment legally unsound.

The impropriety is further exacerbated by the fact that the very judge who authorised the defective warrant had, prior to doing so, issued a directive instructing all law enforcement personnel not to seek judicial authorisation for warrants through any medium other than judicialFLOW. A copy of that directive is attached hereto for the Court’s consideration. The State cannot, on the one hand, rely on a warrant obtained through an expressly prohibited method, and on the other, expect this Court to turn a blind eye to the procedural safeguards enshrined in its own rules.

Respectfully, this Court is duty-bound to uphold the integrity of its rules and procedures. To do otherwise would be to condone the erosion of due process. Because the Search Warrant is procedurally void, and because the indictment is wholly dependent on the fruits of that invalid warrant, I submit that this action must be dismissed with prejudice.

JaroCycle 2025-07-26 01:10 p.m.
Adding to this Your Honor, the defense is cherry picking the local rules of the court, and attempting to turn what is essentialy a minor clerical oversight into a major issue competely ignoring the true purpose of the exclusionary runer under Fourth Amendment. Indiscriminate application of the exclusionary rule, therefore, may well "generat[e] disrespect for the law and administration of justice." Stone v. Powell, 428 U.S. 465, 491 (1976)

“Particularly when law enforcement officers have acted in objective good faith or their transgressions have been minor, the magnitude of the benefit conferred on such guilty defendants offends basic concepts of the criminal justice system.” United States v. Leon, 468 U.S. 897, 908 (1984) (citing Stone v. Powell, 428 U.S. at 428 U. S. 490).

Furthermore, the courts have consistently held that dismissal of criminal charges with prejudice is an extraordinary remedy, reserved only for instances of governmental misconduct that prejudices the defendant’s rights in a manner that no lesser remedy can address.

In United States v. Derrick 163 F.3d 799, 808 (1998), the court held that “dismissal with prejudice is a drastic remedy and should be granted only in cases of willful or egregious misconduct.” Likewise, in United States v. Chapman 524 F.3d 1073, 1084 ( 2008), the court reaffirmed that dismissal with prejudice is appropriate only where “there is flagrant misbehavior and substantial prejudice.”

There is no evidence of any misconduct taking place, the defendant must show that the affidavit contained deliberate falsehoods or reckless disregard for the truth. No such showing has been made here nor has taken place.(edited)

Toby Ellis, Esq. 2025-07-27 06:51 p.m.
Your Honour, if I may respond.

The State refers to this as a minor clerical oversight, but with the greatest respect, that is a mischaracterisation. The rule requiring all pre-court submissions — including warrant applications — to be filed through judicialFLOW is not a guideline. It is a mandatory Local Rule, explicitly stated in District Mayfl. Local Rule 4(7)(1) and reinforced by Rule 4(7)(2), which bars the admission of any case that does not comply with this process.

This isn’t a technicality — it’s a jurisdictional gateway. The Court has made it clear that all pre-court matters must pass through judicialFLOW, and there is no provision allowing judges or law enforcement to bypass that system. When that process is ignored, the resulting warrant is procedurally invalid — it simply has no legal foundation.

The State cites Leon and Stone v. Powell regarding good faith and the exclusionary rule, but those cases deal with warrants that were at least lawfully issued. Here, the warrant was issued in a manner expressly forbidden by the rules of this very Court. There was no ambiguity. The officer and judge involved knowingly sidestepped a rule that exists to ensure transparency, accountability, and proper judicial oversight.

Good faith does not cure a structural defect. This isn’t about what was in the affidavit — it’s about the process being corrupted from the outset. The foundation of the warrant is invalid, and as a result, so is the Criminal Information that flowed from it.

Dismissal in this case is not about punishing the State — it is about protecting the integrity of the judicial process. If the Court allows warrants obtained outside the lawful channel to stand, it invites further violations and renders its own rules meaningless.

Respectfully, we maintain that the proper and just remedy is to suppress the evidence obtained and dismiss the action with prejudice.

JaroCycle 2025-07-29 06:32 a.m.
Hon. HolyRomanRyan who issued the warrant had both subject-matter and territorial jurisdiction to authorize the warrant. The use of the judicialFLOW system, while encouraged under local rules, is not jurisdictional. The absence of strict compliance with an administrative platform does not nullify judicial authority lawfully conferred by the constitution and legislature.

Rule 2(1)(3), Mayfl R. Crim P - ''Search and Seizure warrants shall only be issued upon valid application of probable cause, and that the scope of such searches shall be limited to the probable cause that the item be within such particularized scope.'', allows the judge to have much discretion on how to accept a search warrant application. It does not mandate the usage of the judicalFLOW system, nor identifies any unauthorized ways to submit an application of probable cause. This rule allows a judge to lawfully issue warrant based on on a request made outside of the judicalFLOW system.

The system itself was introduced to prevent judge shopping, and is something that Hon. HolyRomanRyan issued, the same judge who signed the search warrant, and accepted the application via DMs rather than judicalFLOW.

Even assuming that a procedural defect occurred, dismissal of the case is unwarranted under the good faith exception established in United States v. Leon, 468 U.S. 897 (1984). The exclusionary rule is designed to deter deliberate, reckless, or grossly negligent conduct, not to punish officers for relying on a warrant issued by a neutral and detached magistrate.

The warrant here was facially valid, supported by probable cause, and executed lawfully. Law enforcement reasonably relied on the authority of the court and had no reason to question the method of issuance. Nothing in the record supports the conclusion that the officers acted in bad faith, or that the alleged defect was anything more than a ministerial irregularity.

Toby Ellis, Esq. 2025-07-29 08:37 a.m.
First, the State mischaracterises this issue as a mere ministerial or administrative defect. That is plainly inaccurate. This is not about preference or convenience—this is about jurisdiction and the legality of the warrant’s issuance. Under D. Mayfl. LR 4(7)(1), “[a]ll pre-court submissions must be filed through the court’s electronic Discord system, known as judicialFLOW.” There is no discretion afforded to judges to circumvent this requirement, and certainly no provision that authorises judicial action initiated through private messages.

Local Rule 4(7)(2) reinforces this point by stating, “No case will be admitted to the court without completing this process.” That is a jurisdictional bar. The warrant was not properly submitted. It was not properly reviewed. And the case stemming from that warrant never passed through the court’s prescribed gateway for jurisdiction to attach.

Second, while the State cites Rule 2(1)(3) of the Mayflower Rules of Criminal Procedure as giving broad discretion to judges, that rule governs the scope and basis of a warrant—not the method of application or filing procedure. It says nothing about bypassing judicialFLOW or permitting warrant applications via DMs. Reading discretion into that silence contradicts the express procedural mandates of this Courts Local Rules.

Third, the invocation of United States v. Leon is misplaced. The good faith exception cannot revive a warrant that is void ab initio because it was issued ultra vires—that is, outside the judge’s lawful authority. There can be no good faith reliance on a warrant that was issued in a manner explicitly barred by rule, especially when the rule was affirmed by the very judge who signed the warrant.

Your Honour, this is not a minor technicality. The officers only discovered and seized the alleged contraband because of a warrant that, as you rightly noted, was issued outside lawful bounds. There is no lawful path to cure that defect or to re-obtain the same evidence without compounding the violation.

The defence submits that the Court lacks jurisdiction over this case as a direct result of the improper issuance of the warrant. Accordingly, the only just and lawful remedy is to exclude the tainted evidence and dismiss the matter.

JaroCycle 2025-07-30 10:23 a.m.
Judges still have to adher to Rules of Criminal procedure and proper probable cause application and search warrant application, if they are not accepting a SW through judicalFLOW. The spirit of the local rule 4 is to prevent judge shopping, it fails to recognize special circumstances that are granted by rules of criminal procedure and Hon. sadoimpacto whose rule I cited in my previous argument.

Furthermore, the search warrant that we have in this case was posted and executed through the correct channel - warrant-services as every previous warrant whether applied for through judicalFLOW or not. This allows the court to still retain oversight and enforce accountability, even if the warrant like in this case wasn't applied for via judicalFLOW. Like I've said before it is due to the fact that the defendant is an active law enforcement officer, judicalFLOW although a great system doesn't eliminate the risk of possibly leakage of the application especially if the target of the warrant is an active law enforcement officer. Local Rule 4 also does not define submissions, whether it applies only to submissiosn such as criminal information, civil information, notice of apperance, or also to arrest warrant or search warrant, as those aren't always a pre-court submission, as execution of those warrants does not immediatly mean a court case will follow.

Court retains oversight of all warrants, as it is clear beyond doubt who signs them, and can also review the application process and probable cause hearing that follows it if a problem arrises.

Thus the whole issue is more on what you find more important rules of criminal procedure, or local rules. In my understanding, local rules exist to fill gaps that are not adressed by the rules of criminal procedure, in this case rule 4 does not cover special circumstances such as this one.(edited)
